name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson Right, futures markets don't preclude education. (Or anything else, really.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@alpacasw @MrHodl @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson For better or worse, that's just inherently possible on Bitcoin. Miners can de facto restrict the rules.

What this normalizes, if anything, is that signaling and (thereby) facilitating a URSF makes it easy for users to reject the soft fork, if they want to.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @JWWeatherman_ @adam3us @JeremyRubin @bradmillscan @michaelfolkson It will only reflect that stupidity if these bitcoin investors also trade on it (as opposed to concluding that they're not smart enough and should steer clear), AND if there aren't enough smart investors to take advantage of their stupidity (eg. people dumping their B2X futures).

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JeremyRubin @theinstagibbs @ajtowns I think futures markets help prevent real splits, because one side of the debate will probably get a real clear signal that they're betting on a dead horse and give up; and otherwise miners just won't mine the worthless chain.

B2X futures markets are the perfect example of this.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @briangroll @provoost Will consider!

tweet: @BranBTC @BashCo_ @michaelfolkson @BITCOINALLCAPS @JeremyRubin I'm certainly not arguing that splits are *always* beneficial :)

tweet: @JeremyRubin @MrHodl @alpacasw @michaelfolkson Oh, if that's how it works, great :)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JWWeatherman_ @adam3us @JeremyRubin @bradmillscan @michaelfolkson Exchanges will presumably set up features markets if and when they think the ideas are non-silly enough to warrant trading, so they can earn fees.

Really silly ideas will probably be ignored altogether. (Also by markets and miners after the fork.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@MrHodl @alpacasw @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson As long as @JeremyRubin (in this specific case) is honest and transparent about his actions, and ideally even helps facilitate the URSF (insofar that that is necessary-- perhaps coordinate on timing?), I don't see why it should be considered a hijacking attempt.

It's a proposal.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@alpacasw @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson I encouraged big blockers to fork off, too. Without hash power lobbying, without bullying developers, without astroturfing, etc... just pick a block height and deploy the fork.

We've since seen the power of futures markets (B2X). Now I'm even more confident that this is the way.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@adam3us @JeremyRubin @bradmillscan @michaelfolkson Markets have so far in Bitcoin's history shown to respect/follow the opinion of technical experts. I'm sure you remember the B2X futures markets :)

Markets are also very different from populist referendums: https://t.co/52wYk2EGJZ

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@adam3us @JeremyRubin @bradmillscan @michaelfolkson I think futures markets help prevent drama.

If the market prefers ossification, I think we'll see ossification. But at the end of the day, Bitcoin is permissionless free market money; we can't stop people from trying to improve it, and the market is the ultimate arbiter.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@BranBTC @BashCo_ @michaelfolkson @BITCOINALLCAPS @JeremyRubin We can't know for sure, but it certainly seemed like the market was happy with the split.

The specific example doesn't really matter for the overall argument though, as long as we agree it's at least theoretically possible for a split to increase total value.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@adam3us @JeremyRubin @bradmillscan @michaelfolkson I think technical consensus is a good ideal to strive for, especially for Bitcoin Core. But I also don't think it's very well defined, and perhaps more importantly: it probably doesn't scale very well. (Different preferences in tradeoffs will persist.)

Markets do scale very well

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson I'm confused about what you mean by replacing Bitcoin Core maintainers?

Isn't migrating to a new reference client the way to do that?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson So you think Bitcoin Core should always define the consensus rules?

How would we set up a new group of maintainers? Who decides when that needs to happen, and who the replacements should be?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson You won't be forked off if a majority of miners enforce the rules.

But you also wouldn't be a fully validating node. (Eg.: if your node isn't enforcing Taproot rules, it's not a fully validating node.)

This is how soft forks already work.

(Do you disagree?)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson Alternatively, Bitcoin Core de facto defines what is "Bitcoin"...

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@JWWeatherman_ @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson That really depends on how people would use/perceive Bitcoin.

If markets & miners want the soft fork, but Bitcoin Core doesn't merge, then Core essentially (arguably?) wouldn't be a fully validating node after activation, and users should probably migrate to the new SF client...

name: Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @BashCo_ @michaelfolkson @BITCOINALLCAPS @JeremyRubin Defensive soft fork should act as deterrence first, but could also become backwards compatible if it (re)claims the longest (most PoW) chain.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @BashCo_ @michaelfolkson @BITCOINALLCAPS @JeremyRubin I don't agree that chain splits are necessarily detrimental. If the combined value of the split chains is more than the value of a unified chain, for example, splitting is better IMO. (As we did indeed see in 2017.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @specialenmity @SomsenRuben @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson Anyone is free to prefer a minority chain if they think it's better.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@SomsenRuben @JeremyRubin @michaelfolkson The latter... but I'm not really sure why that sentence starts with "Or"?

I do think there are better and worse ways of trying, though. Eg.: there should be plenty of lead time for futures markets to develop and to allow people to make up their minds, etc.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:

https://t.co/2g2SMZzDnL

tweet:

name: Aaron van Wirdum

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:

https://t.co/PhAwP5AuEO

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
Bitcoin Core contributor Gregory Maxwell then figured out how to combine Schnorr and MAST in a clever way to not only make smart contracts more compact, but in many cases also indistinguishable from regular transactions, benefitting privacy: Taproot.

https://t.co/I1mPbRthtt

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
Meanwhile, Bitcoin developers were also thinking about a trick called MAST (Merkelized Abstract Syntax Trees), which would make smart contracts on Bitcoin more compact.

https://t.co/Ub6jdgO4lz

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
Among other things, Schnorr signatures would enable a new type of smart contracts, sometimes referred to as Scriptless Scripts.

https://t.co/uKGy0Kwq5R

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
For years now, Bitcoin developers have been wanting to implement Schnorr signatures on the Bitcoin protocol.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @TheBlueMatt If 2X could've been reorged away, I don't think it would have traded at 10%, it would have traded at ~0%. tweet:
Benefits of LOT=false outlined by Greg Maxwell. (LOT=false means that a Bitcoin client will NOT activate the Taproot upgrade after a year regardless of hash power support, whereas LOT=true means that a Bitcoin client WILL activate it once the year is up.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum

@Cheirut @Truthcoin @AntPoolofficial Yes, but that was a proposed hard fork. (And an unpopular one.) Miners can't activate hard forks; these require that *everyone* upgrades. 

Taproot is a proposed soft fork. Because soft forks are backwards compatible, hash power support is actually helpful during upgrade process.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @adam3us Why do we need a model?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@saifedean @coryklippsten @parabolictrav @bitstein @krugermacro I won't pretend I understand the math, but:

Model is fairly new; most of its predictions have yet to come true.

Not everyone agrees the model proves anything. (Eg.: https://t.co/qYPpqQQq2s)

Not the only model that fits. (Eg.: https://t.co/nUmmPWkvMi / https://t.co/lkJlgY5oGH)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@saifedean @coryklippsten @parabolictrav @bitstein @krugermacro My back-of-a-napkin calculation for today's value would be something like:

Future value once fully adopted as money thanks to S2F etc.
Discounted for: time preference
And discounted for: risk it won't be fully adopted as money

Today's specific S2F ratio seems ~irrelevant to me.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @stanjoll @saifedean @coryklippsten @parabolictrav @bitstein @krugermacro Right, my argument isn't that everything is predictable and can thus be priced in. We can't perfectly predict future adoption, because it's uncertain. So if future adoption happens, price should increase. In contrast, the S2F ratio *is* perfectly predictable. Should be priced in.

tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Ok, so a codebase fork of Bitcoin Core.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream What would make the release a Bitcoin *Core* Taproot release, or is that just a name?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @adam3us Yes, although IIRC it was designed pretty specifically for the btc1 client, or at least with the whole Segwit2X thing in mind. I think that is important context so I decided to mention btc1, but indeed was careful not to claim that miners were in fact running btc1.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @theinstagibbs @Blockstream I'm curious to understand your position, so I'll bite: What's your definition of "everyone" in this context? And by "Bitcoin Core UASF builds" you mean the BIP148 client, right? (Not any of the Bitcoin Core releases that could be downloaded from https://t.co/dOhHXTLmrU?)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream So in your view, this would also require the Bitcoin Core team to release it, using the same requirements for consensus among contributors etc.? (Unlike the BIP148 client, for example.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @theinstagibbs @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Thanks :) I'll rephrase my question: "How do you explain that Bitcoin Core nodes enforced Segwit two years ago?"

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream So you prefer Bitcoin Core not to include BIP8, but if it does include BIP8, it should also include flag day activation. Is that correct?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Since which version has this been hardcoded?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Then how do you explain that Bitcoin Core nodes enforce Segwit today?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @michaelfolkson @MrHodl @Blockstream Yes, I meant the risk for miners in particular.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet:
@LukeDashjr @Blockstream Do you only support BIP8 for soft fork activation at this point?

Also, are you OK with Bitcoin Core including BIP8 configured without flag day activation?

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream That did happen, and is why Bitcoin Core nodes are enforcing Segwit today. (Same for Bitcoin Knots nodes, AFAIK.)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @michaelfolkson @MrHodl @LukeDashjr @Blockstream I guess if you'd ask me I'd say that the risk of letting BIP148 run its course made miners activate BIP91, which in turn triggered BIP9 activation for Segwit.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @michaelfolkson @MrHodl @LukeDashjr @Blockstream BIP91 is mentioned in this Taproot discussion BTW, also included in my article.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @michaelfolkson @MrHodl @LukeDashjr @Blockstream What "actually" activated Segwit kind of depends on who you ask (or: which client they used). I'd actually say everyone would have to agree BIP9 activated Segwit itself. But some argue BIP148 triggered BIP9. Some argue BIP91 triggered BIP9. And some argue nothing triggered BIP9.

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @MrHodl @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Well, not exactly, but...

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream Does this conflict with what I wrote? (If so, how?)

name: Aaron van Wirdum
tweet: @LukeDashjr @Blockstream BIP148 forced BIP9 signaling. So even if you hold the position that BIP148 activated Segwit (not everyone does), BIP9 *also* did.

This confuses many.

Lockdowns are not a policy. They're a policy _tool_. They're part of both the mitigation policy (flatten the curve/herd immunity) and the containment policy (crush the curve/eradicate the virus).

Difference is not whether lockdowns are used, but when and why
